# Discord Chat Analysis for ðŸ’»-tech-support

## 1. Summary:
The chat primarily revolves around ElizaOS development and deployment. Bealers shared two GitHub repositories: eliza-remote (an older project) and elizify (current work in progress), which provides containerized deployment for ElizaOS. The elizify project includes Mattermost integration for a complete end-to-end demo. A significant technical discussion occurred between maikyman and 0xbbjoker regarding plugin development, specifically about integrating custom actions with providers for a web3 app recommendation system. 0xbbjoker provided detailed guidance on setting up dynamic providers, describing providers properly, and using messageHandlerTemplate for agent planning. The conversation highlighted the architecture of ElizaOS plugins, particularly how to use provider outputs in custom actions and how to prevent duplicate responses from REPLY and custom actions.

## 2. FAQ:
Q: Does the agent-twitter-client still exist? (asked by MSG) A: Unanswered directly, but sayonara suggested "use zed + openrouter + free deepseek" as an alternative
Q: How do custom actions and providers work together in a plugin? (asked by maikyman) A: 0xbbjoker provided detailed steps including setting up dynamic providers, describing providers properly, and using messageHandlerTemplate (answered by 0xbbjoker)
Q: Do I need to edit core lib for custom plugin development? (asked by maikyman) A: No need to work in core/plugin-bootstrap, you can change instructions by providing your own messageHandlerTemplate (answered by 0xbbjoker)
Q: Is there an ElizaOS Coolify container? (asked by Reneil) A: Yes, Bealers confirmed the default compose file works with Coolify (answered by Bealers)

## 3. Help Interactions:
Helper: 0xbbjoker | Helpee: maikyman | Context: Building a plugin for web3 app recommendations with custom actions and providers | Resolution: Provided detailed guidance on setting up dynamic providers, using messageHandlerTemplate, and binding providers in custom actions
Helper: Bealers | Helpee: Reneil | Context: Deploying ElizaOS on Coolify | Resolution: Confirmed the default compose file works with Coolify and offered assistance with any problems
Helper: wookosh | Helpee: Reneil | Context: Looking for ElizaOS Coolify container | Resolution: Shared GitHub link to elizify project

## 4. Action Items:

# Analysis of "ideas-feedback-rants" Channel

## 1. Summary
The chat segment contains a brief discussion about an AI trading agent experiencing issues with cryptocurrency trading. User moebius3948 reports that their agent is not selling coins when profitable and is purchasing coins that subsequently experience "rug pulls" (a type of scam where developers abandon a project and run away with investor funds). There appears to be confusion between terminology, as moebius3948 initially refers to their system as a "bot" but is corrected by Dr. Neuro who clarifies that an "AI agent" is different from a "bot." The user expresses concern about whether the issue stems from the AI algorithm itself or possibly because the source code is open, suggesting potential exploitation of known behaviors.

## 2. FAQ
Q: What's wrong with my AI agent buying coins that get rugpulled? (asked by moebius3948) A: Unanswered
Q: Is it a problem of AI algorithm or because they open the source? (asked by moebius3948) A: Unanswered

## 3. Help Interactions
Helper: Dr. Neuro | Helpee: moebius3948 | Context: Terminology confusion between "bot" and "AI agent" | Resolution: Dr. Neuro clarified that an AI agent is different from a bot

# Analysis of ðŸ¥‡-partners Discord Channel

## 1. Summary
The chat primarily revolves around the upcoming V2 launch of AI16Z's agent platform. Key technical highlights include the announcement of V2 agents that will work across chains with 5-minute setup and 40% lower latency. The update includes several technical features: Swarms (multi-agent teams that self-complete tasks), Dynamic Memory (allowing agents to recall preferences), Enhanced TEE (secure enclave transaction processing), CLI with 34 plugins (one-line install with TypeScript types), and RAG (instant retrieval with auto citations). There's discussion about a potential "Agent-to-Agent" (A2A) marketplace where agents would transact autonomously, with AI16Z tokens as the settlement currency. Community members also discussed tokenomics concerns, noting that while tokenomics updates won't coincide with the V2 launch, they are planned for later. A live demo of the V2 platform is scheduled for July 9, 2025.
